segments.text: Your full name, and what about where you were born, and when, and how many years, and how you finally got to Texas A&M.
Noel Parsons, my middle initials are.
Which you never use?
Yeah, I do.
I use it, but I don't spell it out.
I was born and raised in Oklahoma, went to the University of Oklahoma, and got a commission in the Air Force through ROTC there.
Graduated in 64, went right into the Air Force for four years, and realized I didn't want to make the Air Force my career.
You were a pilot, weren't you?
No, I was on flying status, but I was an intelligence officer, and there was a power to navigate.
I did some couriers for this too.
I used to fly into Berlin from Frankfurt to visit our side in Berlin.
asked me to carry the mail.
Oh, it was the line that you gave in the mail to people?
Did you know that was going on?
Oh, yeah.
So where were you stationed most of the time?
I was three years in Frankfurt, on my air base, and met my wife while I was over there.
Oh, did you?
She was an American student.
From where?
She was from Houston.
What school did she go to?
Oh, she was going to a German art school.
Oh, she was going to a German art school, okay.
Okay, she wasn't going to, you know... No, no, she was going to the technical art school in Oakland on our side of the community.
And she was working in Frankfurt, too.
We met at the Poshy Ball in the East Ball.

But at any rate, I decided I didn't want to make the Air Force a career, so I decided to go back to school, use my GI benefits, and went back to the University of Oklahoma and started the master's program in journalism.
And I didn't like newspapers very much, and I was talking to my
advisor one day and told him I really don't know what I want to do with the journalism degree.
He said, why don't you go into book publishing?
I said, hey, about that, I've been interested in books.
He said, yeah, but how do you get into it?
He told me about the fellowship program at the University of Oklahoma Press.
So I tried out all of that and got my way.
I've been in the publishing business ever since.
We had an internship at the journalism school, but it's not the same sort of program.
This was a fellowship, it was paid, and we got experience in several different areas.
We concentrated in conference.
And there were two of us in here.
And that program had been initiated by Savoy Lockerville.
Way back in the early 50s, Jack Kyle, who was director of UT Press, was one of the graduates of the program.
Director of the University of Washington Press.
He retired recently and was a graduate.
Who was the director of Alchemist Press?
Ed Shaw.
Savoy, Lawtonville, just retired a year or two years ago.
So that's S-A-V-O-Y?
S-A-V-O-Y.
I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N-V-I-N He died recently.
Retired in 60, I guess it was 67.
That's a good year for a homeowner.
Yes.
Well, Lawtonville was a big director and a good publisher.
They built their American Indian series, and a lot of the Western exploration books that they did.
They built Altamont.
So you were there for about a year?
I was there a year, in that program, and then I got a job in Detroit, in the Dearborn, actually.
Professional organization, society for manufacturing engineers.
I worked there two and a half years, and they closed their program.
for the Society of Manufacturing Engineers?
There's a chapter here.
And you're doing the editing?
The professional association, you're doing the editing?
Right.
We had a books department.
We published books on manufacturing engineering, and product engineering, and we edited the Manufacturing Engineers Handbook, which was published in October of last year.
It was an interesting experience because there were three of us and we did a little bit of everything.
And then they decided though to close down the book publishing on Rich.
They gave us a month's notice.
Actually, December the 2nd, they let us know that as of the end of the year we were out of there.
Oh, no, no.
Well, that's a typical Detroit moment.
And they gave us a month's notice and said it was on the way.
So I started looking immediately for the person in question.
And how did you get into it?
Why?
Why?
Because I wanted to get back into it.
I really liked scholarly publishing as opposed to trade publishing, all the kind of professional publishing.
And I didn't want to go to New York.
I didn't really want to live in New York.
I was a small town boy.
I just didn't feel comfortable doing something like that.
I put out my resume to everybody in the university press directory.
The only good nipple I got was from Dick Winworth at the University of Illinois, but he was associate director.
You just have to know him real well.
He's a nice guy.
I saw him just the other day in San Francisco.
He must be getting ready to retire.
Who's he with now, you know?
Oh, he's director of Bill and Marla.
Student director of Bill and Marla.
He became director on Sunday before Sunday.
But, uh, he, I went, uh,
I went to Champaign and interviewed with him and then they hired me and I started work there in Marshall since 73.
And then the summer of 75 I went to an AAUP meeting in Brown County, Indiana.
who met with Dick, who's now finally camped out at State Park.
He went to the meeting out of his trailer.
Is that right?
Yeah.

And Mary Stith, who was the managing editor, editor-in-chief at Midwest and both former press, who had managed the fellowship program, who told me that Frank Wardlaw, who I'd always heard of, the great legendary Frank Wardlaw, was starting a new press, the Texas A&M.
And he was looking for an associate editor.
And so she recommended that I talk to him.
And she introduced me to him.
And he said, well, come on up to my room in such and such a time.
We'll have a drink and we'll talk.
And so I went to his room and he gave me
scotch, which I was drinking at the time, and a great big cigar.
I didn't know how to turn down the cigars.
So I sat there and puffed on that cigar, and we talked for a good while.
And he told me what he was doing at 8 AM, and that he was trying to collect
a group of people that would staff a small but active press.
But he wanted to start the press out full grown.
And we would begin publishing about 15 or 16 books a year and continue it that way.
He wanted people who were experienced and
who invited me to come take a look at College Station.
So that was in June.
The next month then Chris and I loaded Claire into the car and we drove to Houston to see her appearance and on the way we stopped at College Station.
We stayed in the Aggie suite, the guest quarters in the house, and Frank and Rosemary showed us all around.
And we drove down to Illinois in an air-conditioned car.
And I dropped out of Texas in July.
Oh, yeah.
And poor little Claire was two years old.
Well, she was three years old.
In case I use the name wrong.
Chris is C-H-K-R-I-R. C-L-A-R.
Okay, so you come into town and you stay at the press quarters.
Yeah, we went right to Frank Roseberry's house, the old press building.
And they showed us around the town.
At the same time, in June, at the meeting, Ed Shaw had told me that he was looking for a competitor to replace Mary Stitt for his retirement.

A&M, I talked to Frank and told him that I had a law firm in New York and Frank said, well, you know, we can, the pay was about the same here on jobs, but Frank said that he would see what he could do about getting money to help with my living expenses.
Ed had told me that he couldn't, he didn't have the money to help us pay Frank Miller.
He was having to work the slave wages in Illinois for two and a half years.
We didn't have any money, so.
Yeah, I know.
We were, we were his church guys at the time, and I just really couldn't afford a move.
And, uh, so Frank then, uh,
When I came to College Station in July, Frank told me that he had to take me to Vegas.
And I found out later that he had gone to the Association of Former Students.
They had provided him.
And so I told him that I would take the job that we would need was to start September 1st.
And so then we went on to Houston and visited Liz's grandparents and her sister who was living there at the time.
Her parents were still living in Europe.
And then we came back through Ballin Station on our way back from the homeowner.
He stayed with Frank and Rose Maria Kinn for a couple of days, and we went to try to find a department.
And it was a bad time of the year to try to find a department.
Late July.
Yeah.
Oh, and also during that visit, Frank took me over to meet Jack Lutz.
It was quite impressive.
He took me to the President, even though he wasn't in the President, actually had the time to visit him and visit with a young editor.
Really, you know, that was just being hired as a copywriter.
So that was quite impressive.
Yeah, a lot of people have mentioned, I was wondering how Wayne was getting the whole perspective of it, but Wayne was very positive about the film.
He was very interested in the film, and he was interested in the people that Frank was talking about, because he asked me about the stories.
I told him I was going to the University of Illinois.
Of course, my hair was not color-linked and I had a handlebar mustache.
And so he thought of the fact that Aggies were very clean-cut and didn't use marijuana or any other drugs, that we were trying to keep the campus straight.
And just by implication, get your haircuts up.
Good thing you didn't interview with butter, eh?
Yeah, that's right.
Taking you to the body shop.
So I began to get the idea that this was quite a bit of work in Illinois.
But we liked it.
It was vibrant and active.
There was so much going on.
Even in the middle of the summer, it was a good place.
It was really moving.
You had not really been here before.
You've been in Houston for a few years.
I'd never been to College Station before.
I'd been all around with Houston and Austin.
And there was a college friend of mine who lived in Houston, and he used to go to Galveston and Houston for summer break, but he never stopped at the bus station.
How about the...
Did you know any of the people who were involved in that?
No, I didn't.
I did write all of that documentation.
And, uh, there's a, a debt market that came to visit that first night we came in July.
Frank Hedlund hit Margaret and later Myra Hinton.
I can't remember if Diane was there, but I doubt it.
So it was, I think it was just Margaret and Ray that hit us.
No, Buck was not there at that time.
I didn't meet him until after I started working.
Guy asked me earlier, what do you remember as one of your happiest times or conditions or something while you were there?
Okay, so when you come back through, how was that?
You visited a couple more days.
Finally found an apartment.
Finally found an apartment and a place to lay toast.
We decided to come in mid-August, made our deposit, and we went down to the city.
Then we went back to Willamette, New York, and then we closed it down right there in New York.
At the same time, I called Ed Shaw and told him he was coming here.
I sometimes regretted that.
I didn't feel it was a great opportunity to learn from one of the top people in the business.
I think it's good I came to Texas, but, you know, I think we have an idea.

But when we came back from Houston to stop and find an apartment, when we got back, Frank had talked to, I remember very distinctly, that he was feeling a little poorly, but he was trying to help us in his most important way.
And we were standing in the hallway of their apartment, and I was talking to him, and all of a sudden he turned white as a sheet.
and just fell over the mountain just like a tree.
He just fainted dead away.
I tried to catch him, but he was a big man.
Oh, yeah.
And I kind of caught his shoulder as he was going down, but it was too late.
And he just fell down on his back.
And I ran and got those for him.
By the time we got back to him, he was coming to me.
I did the same thing.
Yeah.
It's pretty funny when a big man falls flat.
But I remember that very clearly.
I think I did it.
He was a patient most of his life.
He had malaria, he had tuberculosis, been in hospital for a year.
He had heart problems at all times.
You never know what's going on in the face.
In the face, why is he doing it?
In the face activity or in the style of life?
The style of life.
Now, when you come to college and start work, what kind of work do you do?
How would you describe the level of activity or who do you work with?
Well, we were doing 16 books.
Margaret and I were doing all of the copy editing ourselves and working with the authors after.
Frank was doing most of the acquisitions.
It was a very close-knit group.
We had weekly meetings.
We'd all get together and discuss every project we had going.
Frank would tell us about what he felt was coming along in the future.
And so we were all working very closely with all of the projects and all of the books that were published.
And working closely with Ray and the design and the layout.
And I started September 1st, and on September 2nd, the first two books came in.
Chip and Skip.
Elizabeth, John, and the others were great.
So we had the reason to celebrate the rest of the crew, even though I hadn't worked with them for years.
So they made me feel right at home.
I didn't want to starve.
What was your first major project?
I think the first book I worked on was my first book in the Zachary Sponsored Economics series.
It's a Tony Kopp's book, and I can't think of the title of the book yet.
Zachary did not want his name associated with him.
Neither did this guy, Hugh, who we have a photo series.
My question is,
I have not used any.
I use pews and equipment, so if you really wanted to dig, you'd find out who sent the winches out there.
I don't know anything about pews, so he was pretty successful.
Yeah, I know.
Which pew was that?
It wasn't.
Marion.
No, no, no.
P-E-W. P-E-W. Frank got it all with Garbo, too.
And that's why he said, I don't know a lot of P's.
They're always P-E-G-H's.
And I never seen a P as in church before.
It was really cute, that cute letter.
Yeah.
And for the same exact reason, I don't know whether Bozo's name, I don't know.
I'll have to look them up.
Let's see, I don't know.
Somewhere I've got my old blog book.
I suspect now they wouldn't mind having it in there.
I like to do that.
Excuse me.
That's okay.
I didn't know.
I don't know about you.
I knew that...
It's a Monte series, but Monte gave $10,000.
He gave $20,000.
Is that right?
Which is interesting.
At least he really was anonymous.
Yeah.
Tierboden, I believe, was counting the honchos in the tsunami series, but I think he wasn't.
He had been on the first...
the first board.
And I guess he helped try to raise that money to make this project.
Anything else other than the cops?
Well, I was trying to find a law firm.
Oh, okay.
I saw it just the other day.
I'm not going to pull that out.
with Vince Branson's book.
As I understand it, it was being developed by the Agricultural Experiment Station.
So we transferred it over here.
And Frank, in fact, paid them $10,000 for their previous services.
They had done everything up to the point of giving it back.
And so to supplement the prices.
Do you remember any details about that acquisition?
I mean, was it offered?
No, that was before I came.
That was one of the first things.
Well, that, you know, regardless of, you know, the rules.
Yeah.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
Okay.
Okay.

So, let me ask you, in the early months there, or whatever year, did you encounter, in your relationship to the press, a particular faculty or former students who seemed to be intensely involved in press activities?
Oh yeah, such as?
It was Haskell Monroe who was the head of the press committee, and Haskell was very active and very willing to do his costuming at the press, and this too, talking about projects.
had a real diplomatic uh at the time we were really searching for books to fill out that 15 or 16 a year we had to scramble and other people
Maggie's and former students' class, they were very eager to give us an idea of STEM.
That's...
After all these years, we're really just down the drain.
We've done a few books over the years in architecture, but it says that we've never been able to raise any money.
Publications, for example, they always go down the drain.
Now with Malcolm Clark, Cheryl Sears, we're going to be able to get more and more, you know, closer to our next project.
with the school here in Houston.
When I was at Illinois, they probably picked up the title.
And after I got here, he said, oh, I turned around back.
that I decided that the stories in that title were a little too strong.
Was there an audience that you were trying to reach?
There is.
In fact, I was thinking about that.
